"Bhatia A., Pathak H., Jain N., Singh P.K., Singh A.K.","Global warming potential of manure amended soils under rice-wheat system in the Indo-Gangetic plains",2005,"Atmospheric Environment","39","37",,"6976","6984",,,10.1016/j.atmosenv.2005.07.052,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-27544467057&partnerID=40&md5=206901a8294aed385196522fea145e62","Division of Environmental Sciences, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Unit of Simulation and Informatics, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Water Technology Center, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Institut fur Meteorology und Klimaforschung, Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","Bhatia, A., Division of Environmental Sciences, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Pathak, H., Unit of Simulation and Informatics, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India, Institut fur Meteorology und Klimaforschung, Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; Jain, N., Division of Environmental Sciences, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Singh, P.K., Division of Environmental Sciences, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India; Singh, A.K., Water Technology Center, Indian Agricultural Research Institute, New Delhi 110 012, India","Use of organic amendments such as farmyard manure (FYM), green manure (GM) and crop residues is important to improve soil health and reduce the dependence on synthetic chemical fertilizer. However, these organic amendments also effect the emissions of greenhouse gas (GHG) from soil. Influence of different organic amendments on emissions of GHG from soil and their global warming potential (GWP) was studied in a field experiment in rice-wheat cropping system of Indo-Gangetic plains (IGP). There was 28% increase in CH4 emissions on addition of 25% N through Sesbania GM along with urea compared to urea alone. Substitution of 100% inorganic N by organic sources lead to a 60% increase in CH4 emissions. The carbon equivalent emission from rice-wheat systems varied between 3816 and 4886 kg C equivalent ha-1 depending upon fertilizer and organic amendment. GWP of rice-wheat system increased by 28% on full substitution of organic N by chemical N. However, the C efficiency ratios of the GM and crop residue treatments were at par with the recommended inorganic fertilizer treatment. Thus use of organic amendments along with inorganic fertilizer increases the GWP of the rice-wheat system but may improve the soil fertility status without adversely affecting the C efficiency ratio. However, the trade-off between improved yield and soil health versus GHG emissions should be taken into account while promoting the practice of farming with organic residues substitution for mineral fertilizer. © 2005 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Carbon dioxide; Carbon equivalent emission; Greenhouse gas; Methane; Nitrous oxide","Carbon dioxide; Crops; Fertilizers; Greenhouse effect; Manures; Methane; Soils; Urea; Amended soils; Carbon equivalent emission; Greenhouse gas; Soil health; Global warming; fertilizer; green manure; methane; mineral; nitrogen; urea; agricultural emission; atmospheric chemistry; carbon dioxide; global warming; greenhouse gas; methane; soil emission; air pollution; article; farming system; fertilizer application; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; harvest; manure; plant residue; prairie; priority journal; rice; soil chemistry; soil fertility; soil pollution; soil quality; wheat; Carbon Dioxide; Fertilizers; Greenhouse Gases; Methane; Nitrous Oxide; Rice; Soil; Wheat; Asia; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Gangetic Plain; South Asia; World; Sesbania; Triticum aestivum",,"methane, 74-82-8; nitrogen, 7727-37-9; urea, 57-13-6",,,,"Adhya, T.K., Bharti, K., Mohanty, S.R., Ramakrishnan, B., Rao, V.R., Sethunathan, N., Wassmann, R., Methane e